    "text": "4.1  Example: rref and Visualisation \nLetâ€™s use .rref() method to compute a solution of a system then visualise it. Consider the system:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n3x+6y+2z&=-13\\\\\nx+2y+z&=-5\\\\\n-5x-10y-2z&=19\n\\end{align}\\]\nExtract the augmented matrix into a SymPy matrix:\n\n\nCode\nA = sy.Matrix([[3, 6, 2, -13], [1, 2, 1, -5], [-5, -10, -2, 19]])\nA\n\n\n\\(\\displaystyle \\left[\\begin{matrix}3 & 6 & 2 & -13\\\\1 & 2 & 1 & -5\\\\-5 & -10 & -2 & 19\\end{matrix}\\right]\\)\n\n\n\n\nCode\nA_rref = A.rref()\nA_rref\n\n\n\\(\\displaystyle \\left( \\left[\\begin{matrix}1 & 2 & 0 & -3\\\\0 & 0 & 1 & -2\\\\0 & 0 & 0 & 0\\end{matrix}\\right], \\  \\left( 0, \\  2\\right)\\right)\\)\n\n\nIn case you are wondering whatâ€™s \\((0, 2)\\): they are the column number of pivot columns, in the augmented matrix above the pivot columns resides on the \\(0\\)th and \\(2\\)nd column.\nBecause itâ€™s not a rank matrix, therefore solutions is in general form \\[\\begin{align}\nx + 2y & = -3\\\\\nz &= -2\\\\\ny &= free\n\\end{align}\\] Letâ€™s pick 3 different values of \\(y\\), for instance \\((3, 5, 7)\\), to calculate \\(3\\) special solutions:\n\n\nCode\npoint1 = (-2 * 3 - 3, 3, -2)\npoint2 = (-2 * 5 - 3, 5, -2)\npoint3 = (-2 * 7 - 3, 7, -2)\nspecial_solution = np.array([point1, point2, point3])\nspecial_solution  # each row is a special solution\n\n\narray([[ -9,   3,  -2],\n       [-13,   5,  -2],\n       [-17,   7,  -2]])\n\n\nWe can visualise the general solution, and the 3 specific solutions altogether.\n\n\nCode\ny = np.linspace(2, 8, 20)  # y is the free variable\nx = -3 - 2 * y\nz = np.full((len(y),), -2)  # z is a constant\n\n\n\n\nCode\nfig = plt.figure(figsize=(12, 9))\nax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection=\"3d\")\nax.plot(x, y, z, lw=3, color=\"red\")\nax.scatter(\n    special_solution[:, 0], special_solution[:, 1], special_solution[:, 2], s=200\n)\nax.set_title(\"General Solution and Special Solution of the Linear Sytem\", size=16)\nplt.show()"
